   "source": [
    "## Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "UPDATED\n",
    "\n",
    "In 2010, top-selling AAA games like Mass Effect 2, Call of Duty: Black Ops, and Starcraft 2 ran on hardware like Intel Core 2 Duos with 1.8 GHZ, over 2 GB of RAM, and 256 MB/NVIDIA GeForce 8600 GPU. How does the historical shift of listed minimum CPU, GPU, and RAM requirements for such top-selling AAA games compare to the median user specifications of Steam users from 2010 to 2020? Furthermore, is the gap between minimum required specifications and median consumer hardware widening over time, indicating a growing barrier to entry for the average PC gamer?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "From 2010 to 2020, the PC gaming landscape underwent a major transformation as AAA games increased in scale, graphical fidelity, and simulation complexity. These advances led developers to steadily raise minimum system requirements, requiring more powerful CPUs, GPUs, and larger amounts of RAM. However, this rapid increase in software demands did not perfectly align with consumer hardware adoption. While developers pushed toward higher performance baselines, many PC gamers continued using mid-range systems for extended periods, creating a growing gap between required and available hardware.\n",
    "\n",
    "A key factor behind rising requirements was the transition toward multi-core CPU utilization in modern game engines. Earlier titles primarily relied on single-core performance, but by the early 2010s, developers began optimizing engines to take advantage of multiple cores for tasks such as physics simulation, artificial intelligence, and world streaming. This shift increased the baseline expectation for CPUs, as games increasingly depended on parallel processing rather than raw clock speed. At the same time, improvements in console hardware also influenced PC requirements, as cross-platform development pushed developers to target higher-performance systems overall<a name=\"ref1\"></a><a href=\"#fn1\">1</a>.\n",
    "\n",
    "In parallel, GPU requirements increased significantly due to advancements in rendering techniques. Higher-resolution textures, dynamic lighting, and more complex shader systems placed greater strain on graphics hardware. <a name=\"ref2\"></a>Historical analyses of GPU performance and gaming requirements show a clear upward trend in memory and processing demands, with modern AAA titles often requiring several gigabytes of VRAM and significantly more processing power than earlier games<a href=\"#fn2\">2</a>. These graphical improvements were a major driver of hardware upgrades throughout the latter half of the decade.\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite these increasing requirements, data from the Steam Hardware Survey demonstrates that consumer hardware adoption progressed more gradually. The survey, which collects hardware data from millions of users, is widely used by developers to understand the distribution of real-world PC configurations<a name=\"ref3\"></a><a href=\"#fn3\">3</a>. Even in recent years, mid-range GPUs and moderate system configurations have remained the most common among players, rather than the high-end hardware typically recommended for modern AAA titles. This highlights a persistent mismatch between developer expectations and the hardware that most players actually own, reinforcing the accessibility challenges created by rising system requirements.\n",
    "\n",
    "Some prior work that we found was an article posted on Windows Central by Cale Hunt. He analyzed the hardware regression from February 2026 to March 2026, and noticed a drastic decrease in hardware quality. He did this by analyzing the Steam Hardware Survey for those two months, and cross referenced that data with hardware pricing from Spring 2025, to Spring 2026. For the average user the RAM decreased, storage decreased, and the use of higher resolution monitors decreased.<a name=\"ref4\" href=\"#fn4\">4</a> What attributed to this was the volatile pricing at the time. In that time period, RAM prices were up drastically, with storage prices increasing too. With these drastic price hikes, users have to settle on lesser specs, which explains the decrease in hardware.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "This prior work informs us that pricing is volatile, which makes the average hardware that steam users have similarly volatile. This can make analyzing the research question difficult, but it makes us aware of how important the economic variable is to our question, and it's something that we need to be aware of. Understanding this relationship provides important context for analyzing how and why system requirements evolve, and how they impact the broader PC gaming ecosystem.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Footnotes:\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "<p><a name=\"fn1\"></a>1. Fahd Temsamani, “Here’s how game system requirements have evolved over 20 years,” Club386, 2026. <a href=\"#ref1\">^</a></p>\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "<p><a name=\"fn2\"></a>2. TechSpot, “10 Years of GPU Performance & Gaming Requirements,” analysis of GPU performance scaling and demand trends. <a href=\"#ref2\">^</a></p>\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "<p><a name=\"fn3\"></a>3. Steam Hardware Survey (Valve), dataset used to track real-world CPU and GPU usage among PC gamers. <a href=\"#ref3\">^</a></p>\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "<p><a name=\"fn4\"></a>4. Hunt, C. (2026). “I didn't expect these swings”: Steam's March survey reveals PC hardware trends that caught me off guard. Windows Central <a href=\"#ref4\">^</a></p>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "UPDATED\n",
    "\n",
    "We predict that the minimum hardware requirements for AAA games have increased at a faster rate than the median hardware specifications of Steam users. This discrepency stems from the continued use of legacy hardware by consumers, who cannot keep up with the hardware required for modern AAA games that are built for newer models due to cost, availability, and media culture. As a result, the performance gap between required and median consumers' hardware has widened from 2010 to 2020."
   ]
  },
