   "source": [
    "### Video Games Computer Requirements "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This dataset contains information on the minimum and recommended hardware requirements for a large set of PC video games. It includes metrics describing the CPU, GPU, system RAM, VRAM, and operating system, all of which represent the baseline hardware performance needed to run each game. CPU clock speed and turbo speed are measured in gigahertz (GHz), indicating how many billions of cycles per second the processor can execute. Higher clock speeds generally correspond to faster processing and better performance. System RAM and GPU VRAM are reported in megabytes (MB) or gigabytes (GB). During data cleaning, these values were standardized to MB to ensure consistency. RAM determines how much data the system can hold in active memory, while VRAM specifically stores textures, frame buffers, and other graphical assets.\n",
    "\n",
    "This data also included GPU metrics. Shader model and DirectX version indicate the graphical feature set the GPU supports, which determines if a game can run certain lighting models, shading, or rendering pipelines. GPU boost clock, measured in megahertz (MHz), reflects the peak operating frequency the GPU can reach under load. GPU memory bandwidth, measured in gigabytes per second (GB/s), describes how quickly the GPU can transfer data to the VRAM and processing cores.\n",
    "\n",
    "A major limitation of this dataset is that all entries were scraped from a single public website, rather than from multiple independent sources. Relying on one source can have strong source bias, because the completeness, accuracy, and formatting of data depend on how the site presents the requirements."
   ]
  },
